<styl>by <m0>By INA PAIVA CORDLE<ql>
<m1><styl>crline <m0>Herald Business Writer<ql>
<m1><ep>
<m0>  Affluent blacks, NationsBank wants you.<ep>
   In the latest segment-marketing wrinkle, the Charlotte, N.C.-based bank is targeting black entrepreneurs and corporate executives with household incomes between $50,000 and $100,000, as well as black-owned businesses, for loans and other services.<ep>
   It's a strategy aimed at gaining credit-worthy customers in the bank's nine-state area, while boosting its image in black communities. The plan also may help the bank gain favor with federal regulators the next time it wants to acquire another bank.<ep>
   NationsBank's new Professional African-American Market Development unit plans to attract clients through marketing agreements with black professional associations, said Shedrick Barber, senior vice president and national coordinator of the unit.<ep>
   The bank already has signed up Meharry Medical College in Nashville and Washington-based Progressive National Baptist Convention, with 2.5 million members. Through deals the bank makes with an organization, members can get special rates on loans and other services, Barber said.<ep>
   NationsBank will announce its plans at the inaugural Black Enterprise Magazine Entrepreneurs Conference May 1-5 in Orlando.<ep>
   With one million households, the affluent black market has been under<m2><ql>
