<m0>served by major banks, Barber said. Yet the market's attractiveness is hard to beat.<ep>
   Nationwide, black purchasing power (--) personal income after taxes (--) reached $427.3 billion in 1996, a 41 percent increase since 1990, said Jeffrey M. Humphreys, director of economic forecasting at the University of Georgia. During the same period, total purchasing power increased 35 percent.<ep>
   Florida is the eighth fastest-growing state in terms of black purchasing power (--) hitting $22.9 million in 1996, up 51 percent since 1990, he said.<ep>
   ``What the numbers show is the economic power of black consumers,'' Humphreys said. ``Not just the fact that this is a lot of cash, but this segment of the market is growing faster than the market as a whole.''<ep>
   However, Ken Thomas, a Miami banking analyst and minority lending expert, said the downside of NationsBank's marketing strategy is that the bank risks alienating its other black customers. Thomas gives NationsBank good marks in meeting Community Redevelopment Act and fair lending criteria nationwide.<ep>
   But Barber said the bank will not ignore its less affluent black customers.<ep>
   ``We've already had aggressive marketing and product development in the low-to-moderate income census tract community,'' he said. ``And that will remain an ongoing focus of NationsBank.''<ql>
